# Python Import Rules

**ALL imports MUST be at the top of the file.** Never place `import` or
`from ... import` statements inside functions, methods, `setUp`, or any
other non-top-level scope.

This is a hard rule enforced by ruff (PLC0415). Violations break CI.

```python
# BAD — inline import inside a method (PLC0415)
def test_something(self) -> None:
    from speleodb.common.enums import ProjectType
    ...

# BAD — inline import inside setUp
def setUp(self) -> None:
    from speleodb.api.v1.tests.factories import TokenFactory
    ...

# GOOD — all imports at the top of the file
from speleodb.api.v1.tests.factories import TokenFactory
from speleodb.common.enums import ProjectType

def test_something(self) -> None:
    ...
```

The only exception is `TYPE_CHECKING` blocks:

```python
from __future__ import annotations
from typing import TYPE_CHECKING

if TYPE_CHECKING:
    from speleodb.users.models import User  # OK — guarded, not runtime
```
